<Fragment slot="intro">
<p>Dryer vent installation in Los Angeles runs <strong>$149–450 total</strong> depending on the length of the run, how many bends it requires, and whether we're replacing existing improper ductwork or installing from scratch. A short straight run from a first-floor laundry room to an exterior wall is on the low end. A longer run through walls or a ceiling with multiple bends is on the higher end. This page explains exactly what affects the price and what a proper dryer vent installation includes.</p>
</Fragment>

<h2>Why Proper Dryer Vent Installation Matters</h2>
<p>This isn't a cosmetic job. A dryer vent that's installed incorrectly — using flexible foil duct, too many bends, running too long, or exhausting into a wall cavity — is a fire hazard and will cause your dryer to fail prematurely. We've seen LG dryers in Pasadena and Glendale that displayed d80 and d90 error codes from day one because the vent was installed incorrectly when the dryer was first set up. The dryer was new, the vent was the problem.</p>
<p>California building code requires dryer vents to use rigid or semi-rigid metal duct, exhaust to the exterior of the building, and not exceed maximum equivalent length based on the number of bends. We install to code on every job and test airflow before we leave.</p>

<h2>What Affects the Price</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Vent Run Length
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Biggest price factor</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Short run (0–10 ft): $149–220</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Medium run (10–20 ft): $220–320</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Long run (20–35 ft): $320–450</div>
  </div>
  <p>The length of duct from the dryer to the exterior wall is the primary cost driver. Each foot of rigid metal duct, fitting, and labor adds to the total. California code allows a maximum equivalent length of 35 feet (reduced for each 90-degree bend). Longer runs require larger diameter duct or booster fans to maintain adequate airflow.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Number of Bends
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Each 90° bend = 5 ft equivalent length</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Each 90° bend reduces max run by 5 ft</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">45° bends reduce by 2.5 ft</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Straighter runs = better airflow</div>
  </div>
  <p>Every bend in the vent run reduces airflow efficiency. A vent run with three 90-degree bends has an equivalent length 15 feet longer than its actual length. We design the route to minimize bends while still getting the vent to the exterior. In townhouses and condos in Irvine and Burbank where the laundry is interior, this often requires creative routing through walls or ceiling spaces.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Wall or Ceiling Penetration
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Adds $80–150</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Through drywall: $80–120 additional</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Through stucco exterior: $100–150 additional</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Required for any new exterior exit point</div>
  </div>
  <p>If we're creating a new exit point through an exterior wall or ceiling, that requires cutting through drywall or stucco and installing a weatherproof exterior vent cap. Most LA and Orange County homes have stucco exteriors which requires a core drill — that's included in the additional cost above. We patch and seal cleanly around the new opening.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    Replacing Improper Existing Ductwork
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Very common in LA</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Flexible foil duct: must be replaced</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Duct venting into attic or wall: must be corrected</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Includes removal of old material</div>
  </div>
  <p>We find improper dryer vent installations constantly across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County — particularly in older homes and in apartments where the original installation cut corners. The most common violations we see: flexible foil duct (fire hazard, traps lint), vent exhausting into the attic instead of exterior (code violation, moisture damage), and duct runs that are too long for the number of bends. Replacing these costs the same as a new installation — we remove the old material and install properly from scratch.</p>
</div>

<h2>What Proper Dryer Vent Installation Includes</h2>
<p>On every installation we do, regardless of price point:</p>
<p><strong>Rigid metal duct throughout</strong> — no flexible foil, no plastic. 4-inch diameter minimum per code. Semi-rigid aluminum acceptable in the transition section directly behind the dryer.</p>
<p><strong>Correct exterior vent cap</strong> — weatherproof, with a damper that opens when the dryer runs and closes when it doesn't. This prevents birds, rodents, and outside air from entering the duct.</p>
<p><strong>Proper support and securing</strong> — duct supported every 4 feet, joints secured with foil tape (not screws, which catch lint).</p>
<p><strong>Airflow test after installation</strong> — we run the dryer and measure airflow at the exterior cap with an anemometer. We don't consider the job done until we confirm adequate airflow. On LG dryers, this means no d80/d90/d95 codes and airflow you can feel clearly at the exterior cap.</p>
<p><strong>Code compliance</strong> — we install to California mechanical code. If you need documentation for a building inspection or HOA, we can provide it.</p>

<h2>Common Situations We Handle</h2>
<p><strong>New dryer installation with no existing vent</strong> — most common in new laundry rooms or garage conversions. We plan the route, install from dryer to exterior, test airflow.</p>
<p><strong>Replacement of improper existing duct</strong> — remove the old foil accordion duct or plastic pipe, install rigid metal in its place. Most common in older Glendale and Pasadena homes.</p>
<p><strong>Vent rerouting</strong> — existing vent is too long, has too many bends, or exhausts in the wrong location. We replan the route and reinstall. Necessary when dryer location changes or when additions change the building layout.</p>
<p><strong>Vent cleaning plus assessment</strong> — sometimes a cleaning reveals the duct material is too degraded to clean properly and needs replacement. We'll tell you on-site if we find this and quote the replacement before proceeding.</p>

